{
  "texts": [
    "For the many-body state to preserve a symmetry, each shell must be fully occupied or fully empty.",
    "For the first example of spin polarization, every shell consists of two states, so that one should choose an even number of electrons to avoid shell-filling effects.",
    "For the second example of T -symmetry, each shell can have either one (TRIM) or two (non-TRIM) states, making the parity of a symmetric state dependent on the energetics.",
    "In general, this issue is absent if one finds the ground state to be a correlated insulator, but poses a problem when the ground state has a Fermi surface (compensated metals or generic non-integer filling factors).",
    "One should therefore be cognizant of the fact that small symmetry breaking effects for metallic states obtained from HF can arise from shell-filling effects, which can be confirmed, if necessary, by inspecting the Fermi surfaces."
  ]
}